    <string name="create_shortcut_help_read_mode_title">New shortcut · %1$s</string>
    <string name="create_shortcut_help_read_mode_block1"><![CDATA[<b>Where it saves</b> — The shortcut is added to <b>General</b> in Shortcut Hub and to your <b>Favorites</b> strip. To change the name, icon, or order, open Shortcut Hub.]]></string>
    <string name="create_shortcut_help_read_mode_block2"><![CDATA[<b>Keys</b> — Toggle modifiers, then tap <b>one</b> letter or key chip. Chips wrap to more lines on small screens. <b>Advanced</b> lets you type token syntax (e.g. <tt>&lt;CTRL&gt;c&lt;/CTRL&gt;</tt>) instead; choosing a chip clears Advanced.]]></string>
    <string name="create_shortcut_help_read_mode_block3"><![CDATA[<b>Modifiers &amp; Target OS</b> — Button labels match your current <b>Target OS</b> (header in the main app). The first toggle is <b>⌘ / Win / Super</b> (HID Gui), then <b>Ctrl</b>, <b>Shift</b>, and <b>Opt / Alt</b>. Stored shortcuts use the same bits as the keyboard; when you change Target OS, labels and HID mapping update together.]]></string>
